    rationale: "In a hemodynamically unstable patient with known upper GI bleeding, hematochezia (bright red blood per rectum) most likely represents a massive upper GI hemorrhage with rapid intestinal transit \u2014 blood moves through the intestine too quickly for hemoglobin to be oxidized to hematin, producing bright red rather than black stool. This is a critical clinical exception: hematochezia does not always indicate lower GI bleeding. Hemodynamic instability with hematochezia should prompt urgent upper endoscopy, not colonoscopy first. Peptic ulcer perforation into the colon is extremely rare and would present differently.",
