    rationale: "Painless hematuria in an older male with a significant smoking history is the classic presentation of bladder cancer (transitional cell carcinoma) until proven otherwise. Smoking is the single greatest risk factor for bladder cancer. The absence of pain, dysuria, or flank pain makes UTI and urolithiasis less likely. BPH can cause hematuria but is a diagnosis of exclusion after malignancy is ruled out. Urgent urologic evaluation with cystoscopy is the standard of care.",
