    rationale: "In cystitis, bacterial pathogens (most commonly E. coli) produce toxins and trigger an inflammatory cascade that disrupts the urothelial barrier. This mucosal inflammation causes capillary fragility and bleeding, producing hematuria alongside the classic symptoms of dysuria and frequency. Tumor invasion is not the mechanism in a young woman with pyuria and bacteriuria. Renal papillary necrosis and glomerulonephritis present differently and are not consistent with this acute presentation.",
